ncashire, England","Reddish, Lancashire, England":"Reddish, Lancashire, England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Rediche","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Gunter, Hans, Hermann, Juergen, Winfried.","German: variant of   Reich  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Reich","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Kurt, Erwin, Gerhard, Alois, Otto, Volker, Erna, Udo, Wolfgang, Dieter, Egon.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): nickname for a wealthy or powerful man, from Middle High German <i>rīch</i> ‘of noble descent, powerful, rich’, German <i>reich</i> ‘rich’. This surname is also found in France (Alsace and Lorraine), Poland, Hungary, Czechia, Slovakia, Slovenia, and Croatia (see also 4 below).","German: from a short form of a personal name containing the Old High German element <i>rīhhi</i> ‘power, might’."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":28,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705188,"age":37,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705189,"age":72,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705190,"age":103,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Agnes Rediche married Lord Matthew Ridiche before 1278, in Reddish, Lancashire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died after 14 July 1306, in Lancashire, England."},"et":{"–after 14 July 1306":"–pärast 14. juulit 1306","–1306":"–1306","1164–Female":"1164–Surnud","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","before 1278":"enne 1278","bef 1306":"enne 1306","1164":"1164","after 14 July 1306":"pärast 14. juulit 1306","about 1164":"umbes 1164","1290":"1290","1306":"1306","Little Hulton, Lancashire, England":"Little Hulton, Lancashire, England","Reddish, Lancashire, England":"Reddish, Lancashire, England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England"},"fi":{"–after 14 July 1306":"–14. heinäkuuta 1